<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-10-29T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-10-29T09:00:00-05:00" n="676" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d676">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">851.30/94: Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Algiers</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cole</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Algiers</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-10-29T15:00:00+01:00">October 29, 1940—3 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received October 30—2 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>139. Reliable source states, “Local high command of naval forces has
                                received a telegram from Admiral Darlan,<note n="79" xml:id="d676fn79">Jean François Darlan, Minister of Marine in
                                    the French (Vichy) Government.</note> ‘I need French Fleet kept
                                in complete readiness day and night to save our Empire.’”</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Cole</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>